In this situation, you have a few options:

1. Pass the reset function as a prop: You can define the reset function in a higher-level component that has access to both the button component and the component containing the EditorState. Then, you can pass the reset function as a prop to the button component, allowing it to call the function. Here's an example:

```jsx
const ParentComponent = () => {
  const [editorState, setEditorState] = useState(EditorState.createEmpty());

  const resetEditorState = () => {
    setEditorState(EditorState.createEmpty());
  };

  return (
    <div>
      {/* ... other components ... */}
      <Button resetFunction={resetEditorState} />
      {/* ... other components ... */}
      <EditorComponent editorState={editorState} setEditorState={setEditorState} />
      {/* ... other components ... */}
    </div>
  );
};

const Button = ({ resetFunction }) => {
  return <button onClick={resetFunction}>Reset</button>;
};
```

2. Use context: If the component containing the EditorState is deeply nested and passing the reset function as a prop through multiple levels becomes cumbersome, you can use React context to make the reset function accessible to any component within the context. Here's an example:

```jsx
const ResetContext = React.createContext(null);

const ParentComponent = () => {
  const [editorState, setEditorState] = useState(EditorState.createEmpty());

  const resetEditorState = () => {
    setEditorState(EditorState.createEmpty());
  };

  return (
    <ResetContext.Provider value={resetEditorState}>
      {/* ... other components ... */}
      <Button />
      {/* ... other components ... */}
      <EditorComponent editorState={editorState} setEditorState={setEditorState} />
      {/* ... other components ... */}
    </ResetContext.Provider>
  );
};

const Button = () => {
  const resetFunction = useContext(ResetContext);

  return <button onClick={resetFunction}>Reset</button>;
};
```

With this approach, the `resetFunction` can be accessed within any component wrapped in the `ResetContext.Provider`.

These approaches provide different ways to make the reset function accessible to components located above the component containing EditorState. Choose the one that suits your specific scenario and component structure.

